            <h2>The Origin of Frybread</h2>
            <p>
                Frybread has its roots in Navajo tradition, emerging during a challenging period in 1864. As the Navajo were compelled by the U.S. government to embark on
                the 300-mile "Long Walk" from Arizona to Bosque Redondo, New Mexico, they were provided with basic ingredients: flour, sugar, salt, and lard. With these,
                they crafted a simple quick bread, frying it in lard over coals. This became the frybread we know today. As time passed, the basic Frybread recipe extended
                to other tribes, with factors such as boarding schools further propagating its presence in Native American diets. <br> <br>
                Frybread stands as a symbol in Native American culture, embodying the dual sentiments of the pain from colonialization and displacement, 
                as well their enduring spirit and resilience. As expressed by the Smithsonian Magazine, for a multitude of Native Americans, 
                frybread serves as a bridge, binding generations together and anchoring the present to the past.
